<DocsLayout
  title="Security"
  description="Understand the trust model, secret handling, webhook verification, network exposure, and owner responsibilities."
>
  <section>
    <p class="overline">Trust model</p>
    <h2>One owner, one host, narrow access</h2>
    <p>
      MyPaas is a single-node control plane with privileged access to the host Docker
      daemon. Treat the owner account and the MyPaas service as infrastructure administration access.
    </p>
    <p>
      GitHub OAuth authenticates users, but authorization still depends on the MyPaas
      database whitelist. There is no public registration flow.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Control summary</h2>
    <table>
      <thead><tr><th>Boundary</th><th>Control</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td><strong>Dashboard access</strong></td><td>GitHub OAuth plus an explicit database whitelist.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Project environment</strong></td><td>AES-256-GCM encryption at rest, masked display, authenticated reveal endpoint.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>GitHub webhook</strong></td><td>Per-project secret and HMAC-SHA256 signature verification using constant-time comparison.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Project network</strong></td><td>Runtime ports bind locally and project traffic passes through Caddy.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Docker access</strong></td><td>The control plane owns the Docker socket; project containers do not receive it by default.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Database writes</strong></td><td>DB Studio requires a temporary write session and primary-key guards for update or delete.</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Secrets and environment values</h2>
    <p>
      Environment values are decrypted only when an authenticated operation needs them.
      The encryption key belongs to the MyPaas instance configuration and must be backed up
      separately from the database. Losing it makes stored values unrecoverable.
    </p>
    <p>
      Do not paste secrets into issue trackers, deployment names, repository files, or logs.
      Rotate GitHub OAuth, webhook, JWT, database, and Cloudflare credentials after suspected exposure.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Public exposure</h2>
    <p>
      The intended production path exposes Caddy through a configured Cloudflare Tunnel.
      Individual runtime ports stay local. Cloudflare handles public TLS and network-edge
      processing according to the operator's Cloudflare configuration.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Owner responsibilities</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Restrict SSH and operating-system administration access.</li>
      <li>Keep the VM, Docker Engine, Compose plugin, and MyPaas checkout updated.</li>
      <li>Configure, test, and retain database backups outside the running database volume.</li>
      <li>Review repository Dockerfiles and Compose files before deploying them.</li>
      <li>Monitor host disk, memory, CPU, and Cloudflare configuration.</li>
      <li>Remove collaborators and rotate credentials when access is no longer required.</li>
    </ul>
    <aside class="warning"><p>Self-hosting gives the operator control over the infrastructure; it does not eliminate security or operational risk.</p></aside>
  </section>
</DocsLayout>
